{"id":"2008.12140","submitter":"Sana Jahedi","authors":"Sana Jahedi, Timothy Sauer, and James A. Yorke","title":"Structured Systems of Nonlinear Equations","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  In a \"structured system\" of equations, each equation depends on a specified\nsubset of the variables. In this article, we explore properties common to\n\"almost every\" system with a fixed structure and how the properties can be read\nfrom the corresponding connection graph.\n  A solution $p$ of a system $F(p)=c$ is called robust if it persists despite\nsmall changes in $F$. We establish methods for determining robustness that\ndepends on the structure, as expressed in the properties of the corresponding\ndirected graph of the structured system. The keys to understanding linear and\nnonlinear structured systems are subsets of variables that we call forward and\nbackward bottlenecks. In particular, when robustness fails in a structured\nsystem, it is due to the existence of a unique \"backward bottleneck\", that we\ncall a \"minimax bottleneck\". We present a numerical method for locating the\nminimax bottleneck. We show how to remove it by adding edges to the graph.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 26 Aug 2020 15:57:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 29 Aug 2020 23:54:13 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 12 Dec 2020 04:58:02 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 7 Jan 2021 15:56:16 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Sun, 16 Oct 2022 21:38:40 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Mon, 3 Apr 2023 03:10:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-04"}
